{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:56:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:56:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15846"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15846"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.07,0.11,0.75,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68027"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8537"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53492"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7033"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22777"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68027"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA knowledge of the anatomy of the female reproductive system is important in the understanding of the potential sites of fertilisation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of fertilisation in natural conception?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervix","Uterine cavity","Isthmus","Ampulla","Fimbriae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eampulla\u003C/strong\u003E of the fallopian tube is the normal site of fertilisation. This dilated portion of the fallopian tube provides the optimal environment for sperm capacitation and egg fertilisation. After ovulation, the egg is swept into the fallopian tube by the fimbriae and meets the sperm in the ampulla, where fertilisation occurs within 24 hours of ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eisthmus\u003C/strong\u003E is the narrow portion of the fallopian tube closest to the uterus. While sperm must pass through this region to reach the ampulla, it is not the usual site of fertilisation as its narrow lumen is less conducive to the fertilisation process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efimbriae\u003C/strong\u003E are finger-like projections at the distal end of the fallopian tube that sweep the ovulated egg into the tube. While essential for conception, fertilisation does not typically occur here as sperm have not yet undergone necessary capacitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervix\u003C/strong\u003E acts as a reservoir for sperm and produces fertile cervical mucus around ovulation, but fertilisation does not occur here. The cervical environment is not suitable for egg survival or fertilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Euterine cavity\u003C/strong\u003E is where implantation occurs 6-12 days after fertilisation, but it is not the site of fertilisation. By the time the fertilized egg reaches the uterus, it has developed into a blastocyst ready for implantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter fertilisation in the ampulla, the developing embryo takes 3-4 days to travel down the fallopian tube to reach the uterus, undergoing several cell divisions along the way. This journey is facilitated by both ciliary action and tubal peristalsis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fertilisation normally occurs in the ampulla of the fallopian tube within 24 hours of ovulation.","The ampulla provides the optimal environment for sperm capacitation and fertilisation.","After fertilisation, the developing embryo takes 3-4 days to travel down the fallopian tube to the uterus."],"references":["Ikawa M, Inoue N, Benham AM, Okabe M. Fertilization: a sperm\u0027s journey to and interaction with the oocyte. J Clin Invest. 2010 Apr;120(4):984-94. doi: 10.1172/JCI41585. Epub 2010 Apr 1. PMID: 20364096; PMCID: PMC2846064.","Coy P, Garc\u00eda-V\u00e1zquez FA, Visconti PE, Avil\u00e9s M. Roles of the oviduct in mammalian fertilization. Reproduction. 2012 Dec;144(6):649-60. doi: 10.1530/REP-12-0279. Epub 2012 Oct 1. PMID: 23028122; PMCID: PMC4022750.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53492"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15846"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53492"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T17:09:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T17:09:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8537"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68027"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attribute